 <p class="text-lg text-slate-700 italic"><strong>"What if the next charger you ship could be 40% smaller, run 30% cooler, and still deliver 240W?"</strong></p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">That's not a future promise. It's GaN V, the fifth generation of gallium nitride technology, and it's already shipping out of Shenzhen factories right now. If you're sourcing chargers for your brand, you've seen the problem: silicon-based chargers are hitting physical limits. Higher wattage means bigger size. GaN V changes everything, higher efficiency, smaller transformers, less heat, more power.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">The global GaN charger market was valued at <strong>$1.4 billion in 2025</strong> and is projected to reach <strong>$3.7 billion by 2030</strong> (CAGR 20.8%, BCC Research 2025), with China accounting for approximately 65% of production. Meanwhile, the <strong>EU Ecodesign Regulation 2025/2052</strong> now mandates standby power below 0.1W, a threshold many silicon designs cannot meet, making GaN V the only practical choice for new products destined for European markets.</p>
 <p class="text-slate-600 leading-relaxed mt-4">This guide covers what GaN V actually means, how to evaluate real GaN manufacturers, and key questions before placing your OEM order.</p>
